 {"id":"bd-3uo1","title":"WS2: Eliminate Static String Allocations in Classification","description":"PROBLEM: rch-common/src/patterns.rs lines 307-410 contain 18 .to_string() calls on string literals/variables during the classification hot path. These allocate heap Strings that are compared and immediately dropped on the reject path (>95% of calls).

Breakdown of the 18 allocations:
- 6x tier name strings ("instant_reject", "structure_analysis", "keyword_filter", "never_intercept", "full_classification")
- 6x reason strings ("command present", "no pipes/redirects/backgrounding", "no compilation keyword", etc.)
- 4x cmd/normalized.to_string() for the classified_command field
- 2x other

WHY IT MATTERS: The 5-tier classification has a <5ms budget. 18 allocations at ~50-100ns each = ~1-2μs of pure allocation overhead per call. On the reject path, this should be zero.

SOLUTION: Use &'static str for tier names and reason strings. Use Cow<'static, str> for classified_command (static on reject, owned on accept). Only allocate when classification succeeds and needs to return an owned result.

SECONDARY: rch/src/cache.rs line 181 — normalize_key() calls command.trim().to_string() on every lookup.

FILES: rch-common/src/patterns.rs (lines 307-410), rch/src/cache.rs (line 181)
RISK: Medium — touches core classification, needs testing to ensure no behavioral changes.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-01-29T17:36:17.258697091Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-01-30T03:52:15.948064730Z","closed_at":"2026-01-30T03:52:15.947967950Z","close_reason":"All sub-tasks complete: WS2.1 (static str slices) CLOSED, WS2.2 (pattern matching) CLOSED, WS2.3 (cache key normalization) CLOSED, WS2.4 (unit tests) CLOSED. Classification uses Cow<'static, str> for tier names and reasons. Cache lookups use &str via Borrow trait.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-3uo1","depends_on_id":"bd-2mmt","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-01-30T16:45:50Z","created_by":"import"}],"comments":[{"id":88,"issue_id":"bd-3uo1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"BACKGROUND: The classification system runs on EVERY command, and >95% of commands are rejected (not compilation). On the reject path, we want zero heap allocations. Currently, pattern sets are rebuilt as Vec<String> on each call, meaning even a simple 'ls' command triggers ~15 String allocations just to build the pattern table before comparison begins.

DESIGN PRINCIPLE: The 5-tier classification was designed for <5ms total. Individual tiers should be <1ms. Eliminating allocations on the reject path keeps Tier 2-3 well under budget.

ALTERNATIVE CONSIDERED: lazy_static! or once_cell for the pattern Vecs. This would allocate once but still use String. Using &'static str is cleaner — the data is truly static and known at compile time. The compiler can place it in .rodata.","created_at":"2026-01-29T17:39:04Z"}]}
